The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, March 12, 2004 				 Bata chairman bows out
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Mudaliar: Hangs up boots																								Calcutta, March 11: A. L. Mudaliar has stepped down as chairman and director of Bata India Limited.																								The Bata board has appointed Constantin Salameh, director (business development), as acting chairman. 																								Mudaliar was a member of the board for nearly two decades and chairman since 1989.																								At a meeting on Wednesday, the board recounted the number of strategic decisions taken under Mudaliars leadership and the plans developed by him to ensure a strong foundation for the company.																								Chandu Morzaria, executive vice-president of BSO Worldwide, has also decided to retire as he is approaching the traditional age at which Bata executives call it a day, a release said. Morzaria is also regional executive of Bata Asia and Africa and vice-chairman of Bata India.																								He has held several senior executive positions at Bata headquarters in Toronto, Canada.																								His resignation was accepted by the board which recorded his dynamic leadership and entrepreneurial spirit in generating higher growth.																								The company has not yet named any person who will be appointed in his post. It may be an expatriate also, said a senior official.																								Over the past few years, Bata has seen a lot of restructuring  the recent being the shifting of many of its operations, including the corporate headquarters from the city. It has also witnessed frequent reshuffling of its top-brass in the past few years. But the frequent changes in strategy and top management has not yielded required results.																								Bata India has been reeling under losses for the last two years. In the nine-month period ended September 30, 2003, the company suffered a loss of Rs 11.7 crore. In 2002, it had suffered a net loss of Rs 7.4 crore. 
